title: For Sale:  Pro Mag Archangel M1A Stock
postcontent: Hello! I have a Pro Mag Archangel M1A Carbon Fiber Reinforced Polymer Stock that I want to go to a good home. I installed this stock on my Armscorp M14 but have decided to take the rifle back to a more historic look. Therefore I would like this stock to go to a good home where it will be used as intended, rather than sit in a closet for a few years. The stock was installed by a gunsmith locally. He shaved about 1/64th of an inch out of the interior to get the receiver to fit. Based on my understanding of the instructions, the archangel stock is built too small on purpose. You shave it to get it to fit. Even with the minor shaving, we had to lube the heck out of the receiver to get it to fit (insert whatever joke you have here for similar situations.) By contrast, the original GI stock I purchased to return the rifle back to the historic look allows the receiver to slide in and out without much effort at all. The Archangel stock is very snug, so don't be suprised if you have to shave it further to get your rifle to fit. However, the lugs where the rifle mates to the stock are unmodified, meaning the points where your receiver actually mates is quite snug, as it should be. The stock certainly improves the ergonomics of the rifle. I personally did not notice much of an accuracy increase (that being said, I'm new to shooting long range, so that may be my lack of skill showing.) That being said, I believe the primary philosophy of use for the stock is to improve the ergonomics. If you want something that will fix the cheek weld with a scope, this is your stock. The stock does have forward mounted polymer picatinny rails for accessory or bipod attachment. The rail does have a cover when not in use, which is also included. If you have any questions please let me know. Thanks for looking!

title: For Sale/Trade:  Custom ATI 1911
postcontent: Up for sale or trade is a highly customized ATI M1911GI-E. This is a commander sized 1911, 4.25" barrel.  White dot front sight, all black serrated rear.  Short reach trigger, skeletonized commander hammer, flared bearvertail and black rubberized grips.  That's how the pistol came, now for the customizations, all of which were perfomed by a certified gunsmith.Slide work: Back end of slide is serrated to reduce glare, 11 degree target crown blended into barrel bushing, ejection port was lowered and flared, the extractor was tuned and the Marvel cut was added to smooth out the action.Frame work:The fronstrap was hand checkered to 30 LPI, as were the front of the trigger gaurd and the bump on the grip safety.  Also, the mainspring housing, mag catch and reciol spring plug were replaced with chekered ones.  Trigger job to about 4 pounds, minimal take up and breaks like a glass rod.  The trigger gaurd is undercut and the beavertail was raised, making it incredibly comfortable in the hand and also giving it great pointability.  The beavertail was radiused to give it a sleeker look, as was the the thumb safety.  Also, the thumb safety, grip safety and frame have been blended together to be one smooth curve.  Again, super comfortable in the hand.  Idiot proofed the slide stop (makes for easy installation and eliminates the chance for the infamous idiot scratch).  The magwell has been beveled as well.It was recently Cerakoted.  The Slide, frame and mainspring houseing are Tungsten (metallic dark grey), all other parts and pins are Cobalt (metallic black).  It's a pretty slick looking firearm.  It comes with 3 mags.  One Springfield 7 round that works great, an 8 round ACT mag that could use a new spring.  The first round tends to nose dive but cycles fine after that.  Also a 10 round promag that I picked up in a trade.  It looked like someone went at with some pliers and I was rather skeptical of it.  It worked surprising well though.  Sticks a bit on the release.  As you can see, quite a bit of work has been put into this little fella and I'm asking a more than fair price. So no lowball offers please.  I also have a pair of Crimson Trace Chainmail grips for sale for it for $150. I can text more photos with details if you're interested. Thanks for looking.
